snippet.textDisplay: It looked terrific? Oh dear, Mark. If top of your list when commending this narrative mess is, "it looked terrific", then we're already scraping the bottom of the compliments barrel. It's Disney. Of course it's gonna look good. They've got billions to spend. But looks age; effects date, and all a movie ever has left are characters. That's why the OT is timeless, and why the sequel trilogy comes in for such flak. Normally you're a great champion of character-driven cinema, Mark. Which is why I'm agog at how you can justify the path taken by TLJ. Forget how it looked... It ignored the world-building, it ignored the in-universe rules, and it ignored the history of the characters. TROS was a fan fiction movie made out of desperation. Why? Because of the crimes and misdemeanour committed by Johnson. And it's sad. So very sad. No reason to talk about the plot? Would you have said the same about the OT? The prosecution rests.

snippet.textDisplay:
The Last Jedi was a terrible film with its numerous contrivances awkward comedy and meandering plot. Rain Johnson attempted to be clever by hitching his story to a philosophy of subverting expectations. In catering to that philosophy of subversion at every point, he manufactured a clunky, inorganic story.
What makes me upset is how film critics that I respect seemed to overlook all the clunky elements they would normally point out about other films and give this film high marks just for being different. Post modern storytelling can be refreshing if executed well. But TLJ failed in the execution.

snippet.textDisplay: Now we have all three films to look at, the decision to give TLJ to Rian Johnson seems more mental than it did when his attachment was announced. All three films by JJ would have led to a basically safe retread of the original trilogy, updated for a modern audience: fine. All three films by Rian Johnson would have led to a radical re-imagining of the whole shebang, and a chance to create something fresh out of a stock formula: also fine. Instead, TFA, while being a little too safe, built a house that TLJ gleefully set fire to, leaving TRoS to try to pick up the pieces; and so the audience who wanted something familiar, and the audience that wanted something different, were both left disappointed by the whole endeavour.

snippet.textDisplay:
Although I think that the hate and vitriol was way way excessive, I think its fair to say the last film was a complete marmite movie. I have friends that liked it and others (like me) that thought it was awful. For me it threw out everything that was set up by JJ Abrams in the first film and had way too many funny in a wrong way moments. Princess Lea Mary Poppins for example. To save time I think this video says it all https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5ECwhB21Pnk&t=887s
I think the fact that Mark Hamill hated it so much and that some of the present cast said it was 'off' says it all for me. That said those people that have sent threats and abuse to people over this really need a reality check. It's a film, an important film for some of us, but just a film.
Having said all that though I think people forget episodes 1-3 which were also a horrible mess, and these were from the great George Lucas himself!

Did you hear that Disney has just bought Gone With The Wind! They will make a sequel but Rhett Butler will be dead and Scarlett Ohara will only serve as a minor character as a mentor for a band of new Southern belles. The critics are saying its breathing new life into The Gone With the Wind franchise with the shocking new twist that the South wins the American Civil War. Amazing! Aren't you excited to see Gone With the Wind 2? 


Wow! Disney bought another property. This time it's Alice Walker's The Color Purple. The sequel will be released next year. Disney wants to expand the Purple universe outside of Celie's story and focus on a white social worker instead. Nettie unfortunately will die off screen and Celie will serve as only a mentor to the social worker. In a shocking twist, Mister's abuse of Celie was only a dream. Critics are praising the franchise's bold new direction. The movie will be a passing of the torch to the next generation. 


Both films to be Co-directed by Rian Johnson and JJ Abrams.



You understand why Star Wars fans hate Disney Star Wars?

snippet.textDisplay: Didn’t want a evolving and progressive story with Last Jedi. Any sequel is fan service and Johnson went for stylish independent filmmaking with Last Jedi rather than stick to the canon ideology and aim. Rise of Skywalker saves everything fans love dear about the series. It’s not about taking it in new directions. We only had one more film of the Skywalker story. We just needed to see it out the way we always have enjoyed it. If fans wanted evolving stories and new directions, then watch Johnson’s new trilogy or The Mandalorian. It didn’t need to be done with the important second part of the last series of the original story. Last Jedi betrayed everything that Luke stood for I the first trilogy. After all his fighting against killing in the first trilogy, he gets a sniff that Kylo could be evil and decides to kill him? Ridiculous and totally out of character and Hamill even said so. This film saves everything and now fanboys of Last Jedi can glory what they want with separate stories away from the Skywalker saga. Should never have been done until after it was concluded though.

snippet.textDisplay:
I enjoyed it. I laughed - mainly at the myriad of call backs and the exposition - but I still don't think Mark understands why TLJ upset so many fans. And even more intrigued as where Mark thought RJ (who I can't believe didn't know what he was doing and was far from as cool as he has tried to make out to you) was taking it? There's been hate on both sides over TLJ but everyone who comments on either side seems to get tarred with the same brush and the people responsible for that film have sadly joined in. But Twitter is the world we live in ... unfortunately.
I think Mark's review is fair. It's certainly no "Empire". There may be bigger fans of Mark (they must be really big) than me but it will be a sad day when I no longer hear or read his thoughts.

snippet.textDisplay: Honestly, I felt like this movie gets more stick than it deserves and it does well to recover from the mess that was The Last Jedi. It fixed the Rey’s parents were nobodies situation it kind of gave more reason to the existence of Snoke other than just sitting in a chair and it sidelined the pointless annoying Rosie character. Although, the ending felt a bit rushed and not very emotional considering that it was the end of the entire saga. The ending on Endor with the force ghosts at the party was epic, I know they couldn’t recreate that but I wanted something a bit closer to it. Considering the circumstances of the last movie and how it kind of closed the door to many ideas, I think JJ did a decent job with this movie.
